definition.value: The amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of F420-0 with the amino group of L-gamma-glutamyl-L-gamma-glutamyl-L-glutamic acid.
An N-glycosyl compound consisting of a heteropolycyclic ring system with a glucosyl group attached to one of the indolic nitrogens.
The penta-anion obtained by removing protons from the phosphate and carboxylic acid groups of coenzyme alpha-F420-3.
The (S)-enantiomer of rolipram.
The tetra-anion obtained by removing protons from the phosphate and carboxylic acid groups of coenzyme gamma-F420-2.
The tri-anion obtained by removing protons from the phosphate and carboxylic acid groups of coenzyme F420-1.
Any antigen that is a phosphorylated microbial metabolite which activates an immune response in humans.
The dianion formed by removal of two protons from the phosphate group of 2,5-diamino-6-(1-D-ribosylamino)pyrimidin-4(3H)-one 5'-phosphate.
5-O-Phosphono-beta-D-ribofuranose in which the hydroxy group at position 1 is substituted by the 6-amino group of 2,5,6-triaminopyrimidin-4(3H)-one.
Any member of the sub-set of polyunsaturated fatty acid for which there is an absolute dietary requirement.
The alpha-anomer of L-idopyranose.
An optically active mycolic acid having one hydroxy and two olefin functions at respectively positions 3, 23 and 33 of the side-chain.
Any fatty acid with a chain length of between C6 and C12.
A piperidine N-oxide having a dimethylphenylsilyl substituent at the 4-position.
Piperidin-2-one N-protected by t-Boc.
A vinyllithium compound bearing an ethoxy group at the 1-position.
A fatty acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxylic acid moiety of a medium-chain fatty acid.
Any porphyrin compound produced from a protoporphyrin by the addition of a hydrogen to the double bond of each of the vinyl groups.
A tetrahydropterin that is 2-amino-5,6,7,8-tetrahydropteridin-4(3H)-one in which a hydrogen at position 6 is substituted by a 1,2-dihydroxypropyl group (6R,1'R,2'S-enantiomer).
An  organic anion that is the conjugate base of diamino acid.
The conjugate base of 5-hydroxyisouric acid.

A glycosylmannose comprising a beta-D-galactopyranose residue in (1->4) linkage with D-mannopyranose; which can inhibit Leishmania major glycoinositol phospholipid binding by sera from patients with acute cutaneous leishmaniasis.

Propane-1,3-diamine in which a hydrogen attached to one nitrogen is substituted by a 3-aminoprop-1-yl group, and a hydrogen attached to the other nitrogen is substituted by a 4-aminobut-1-yl group. A polyamine natural product, its name arises from its similarity to spermine and the fact that it was first isolated from the extreme thermophile, Thermus thermophilus.
An N-[4-(4-nitrophenylphospho)butanoyl]alanine that has S at the chiral carbon.
An alanine derivative having a 4-(4-nitrophenylphospho)butanoyl group attached to the nitrogen of alanine.
The (R)-enantiomer of clenbuterol.
The (S)-enantiomer of clenbuterol.
The monohydrochoride salt of (R)-clenbuterol.

The monohydrate form of ipratropium bromide. An anticholinergic drug, ipratropium bromide blocks the muscarinic cholinergic receptors in the smooth muscles of the bronchi in the lungs. This opens the bronchi, so providing relief in chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and acute asthma.
The monohydrochloride salt of (S)-clenbuterol.
An amino disaccharide consisting of an N-acetylglucosamine having an N-acetyl-9-O-acetylneuraminic acid attached via an alpha-(2->6)-linkage.
A mannan consisting of repeating mannosyl units joined via beta-(1->2)-linkages.
A glycosyl group corresponding to the oligosaccharide portion of glycoprotein BclA.

A disaccharide derivative consisting of alpha-L-rhamnose having a 3,6-di-O-methyl-beta-D-glucosyl residue attached at the 4-position; corresponds to the carbohydrate portion of synthetic antigens containing the Mycobacterium leprae-specific epitope.
A (1->2)-beta-linked trimannosyl group corresponding to the minor beta-mannan component of the phosphomannan of clinically important Candida strains.
A (1->2)-beta-linked dimannosyl group corresponding to the minor beta-mannan component of the phosphomannan of clinically important Candida strains.
A glycosylgalactose consisting of D-galactose having an alpha-D-galactosyl residue attached at the 6-position.
A branched N-glycan derivative that is an undecasaccharide derivative consisting of nine D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues (one at the reducing end).
A branched amino pentasaccharide consisting of two D-glucose residues (one at the reducing end), one N-acetyl-D-glucosamine residue, one D-galactose residue and one L-fucose residue, linked as shown.
A polysaccharide that is a branched dodecasaccharide consisting of three repeating tetrasaccharide units; reported to be a possible epitope of the O-antigen polysaccharide in Salmonella.

16alpha-Methylpregna-1,4-diene-3,20-dione bearing hydroxy substituents at the 11beta and 21 positions, fluorine at position 6 and chlorine at position 9. A medium potency corticosteroid, it is used as its 21-O-pivalate or caproate ester for the relief of inflammatory and pruritic (itching) skin disorders.
The 21-O-pivalate ester of clocortolone. It is used for the relief of inflammatory and pruritic (itching) skin disorders.
A glycosylmannose consisting of D-mannose having an alpha-D-mannosyl residue attached at the 2-position.
The dianion resulting from the removal of two protons from clondronic acid.

The disodium salt of clodronic acid. It inhibits bone resorption and soft tissue calcification, and is used (generally as the tetrahydrate) as an adjunct in the treatment of severe hypercalcaemia associated with malignancy, and in the management of osteolytic lesions and bone pain associated with skeletal metastases.

The tetrahydrate of the disodium salt of clodronic acid. It inhibits bone resorption and soft tissue calcification, and is used as an adjunct in the treatment of severe hypercalcaemia associated with malignancy, and in the management of osteolytic lesions and bone pain associated with skeletal metastases.
